{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "An overview of nuclei and anti-nuclei production with results from different experiments are discussed. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The comparison of data with the thermal and coalescence models is also discussed to understand their production mechanisms in high energy collisions.",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The Universe started with a big-bang with nearly equal abundance of matter and anti-matter. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "However, this symmetry got lost in the evolution of the universe with no visible amounts of anti-matter being present. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The production of light (anti-)nuclei including (anti-)hypernuclei in high energy heavy-ion collisions may be related to the matter-antimatter symmetry. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The production of light (anti-)nuclei has been studied in the vast energy range in heavy-ion collisions experiments at Bevalac, AGS, SPS, RHIC, and LHC. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The two proposed production mechanisms for the (anti-)nuclei are the coalescence model [1] and the statistical thermal model [2]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 87,
                    "end": 90,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 125,
                    "end": 128,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The simple coalescence model assumes that (anti-)nuclei are formed if the constituents baryons are close in the coordinate and the momentum phase space. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The thermal model predicts the dependence of the particle yields of mass m on the baryon chemical potential (\u00b5 B ) and chemical freeze-out temperature (T chem ) by the relation dN /dy \u221d exp((\u00b5 B \u2212 m)/T chem ).",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Results and Discussions",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "In coalescence mechanism, the spectral distribution of the deuterons is related to that of primordial protons via E d",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": ", assuming that protons and neutrons have the same momentum distribution. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "B 2 is the coalescence parameter for deuteron with momentum of p d = 2 p p . ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 1 (left) shows the energy dependence of the coalescence parameter B 2 . ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Figure 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It decreases from Bevalac to SPS energies, then remains almost constant up to RHIC energy [3]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 90,
                    "end": 93,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "From RHIC top energy to LHC energy B 2 shows slight decrease [4]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 61,
                    "end": 64,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[4]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In the coalescence picture, this behavior is explained by an increase in the source volume i.e the larger the distance between protons and neutrons which are created in the collision, the less likely is that they coalesce. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "At RHIC energies, it is observed that elliptic flow (v 2 ) of light (anti-)nuclei when scaled with mass number follows arXiv:1807.02656v1 [hep-ex] 7 Jul 2018 v 2 of (anti-)protons suggesting that light (anti-)nuclei are produced via coalescence mechanism [5]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 255,
                    "end": 258,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[5]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "However, the preliminary results from ALICE suggest that simple coalescence model fail to describe (anti-)deuteron v 2 at LHC energy [6].",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 133,
                    "end": 136,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The right plot of Fig. 1 shows the energy dependence of experimentally measured deuteron to proton ratio in heavy-ion collisions [4,7]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 18,
                    "end": 24,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 129,
                    "end": 132,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[4,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 132,
                    "end": 134,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The comparison is made with the thermal model predictions which seems to explain the data well. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "It is observed that for a given collision energy, T chem and \u00b5 B remain same for heavy-ion and small collisions system. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "At LHC, the d/p ratio for p-Pb and pp collisions is smaller than in Pb-Pb system [8]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 81,
                    "end": 84,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This observation could not be explained by the thermal model. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "For a given system and energy, the thermal model suggests that the nuclei yields follow an exponential decrease with the mass which is consistent with the experimental results. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "One has to pay a \"penalty factor\" to produce the heavier nuclei or each added nucleon [8]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 86,
                    "end": 89,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 2 (left) shows the penalty factor as a function of energy for heavy-ion collisions [7]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 15,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Figure 2 (left)"
                },
                {
                    "start": 90,
                    "end": 93,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The markers show the experimental results (solid symbols for nuclei and open symbols for anti-nuclei) while the curves represent the thermal model predictions. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The thermal model predictions are consistent with the heavy-ion experimental results within the uncertainities. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "However, this is not true for the smaller systems. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "For example, it is observed that penalty factor is about 600 for p-Pb collisions at LHC [8] which is well above the thermal model expectation at this energy. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 88,
                    "end": 91,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This deviation from thermal model expectation in smaller collision systems needs theoretical explanation.",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The right plot of Fig. 2 shows the experimental measurements of hyper-triton ( 3 \u039b H) lifetime from various experiments [9]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 18,
                    "end": 24,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 120,
                    "end": 123,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[9]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The figure also shows the lifetime of the free \u039b from the PDG and measurement from STAR. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 83,
                    "end": 87,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "STAR",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The recent experimental results from STAR [9] and ALICE [10] suggest that the 3 \u039b H lifetime is less than that of free \u039b. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 42,
                    "end": 45,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[9]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 56,
                    "end": 60,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[10]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 78,
                    "end": 79,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "3"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 37,
                    "end": 42,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "STAR",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It will be interested to understand the theoretical explanation of the observed difference in lifetime of 3 \u039b H and free \u039b. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 106,
                    "end": 107,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Recently, the ALICE experiment has measured the mass and binding energies of nuclei and anti-nuclei and found it to be compatible within uncertainties. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "This confirm the CPT invariance of light nuclei [11]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 48,
                    "end": 52,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "[11]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The Quantum Chromodynamics (QCD) predicts the existence of exotic bound states of baryons [12]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 90,
                    "end": 94,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The thermal and coalescence models explain well the experimentally measured yields of light nuclei and hypertriton [4]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 115,
                    "end": 118,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[4]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "These models may predict the yields of exotic bound states and hence may provide baseline to test the existence of these states. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Various experiments attempt to search for these weakly decaying bound state of baryons. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Recently, ALICE has tried to search for the \u039b\u039b and \u039bn bound states [12]. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 67,
                    "end": 71,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "No evidence for these bound states is observed. ",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Theoretical explanation is needed to understand the non-observation of these states.",
            "section": "Results and Discussions",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Summary",
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Light (anti-)nuclei measurements have been performed by various experiments. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The thermal model seems to describe (anti-)(hyper-) nuclei production well in heavy-ion collisions. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "However, deviation from thermal model is seen for small collision systems, the simple coalescence model could explain (anti-)nuclei production in small systems. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "More work is needed on theoretical part to understand the production mechanism of nuclei and anti-nuclei in high energy collisions.",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig. 1 .",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
